ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-9 He was over flying the Picayune Airport at 2,500 feet when he observed smoke coming up from behind the firewall followed by flames. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-1 This is preliminary information, subject to change, and may contain errors. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-11 He and the passenger exited the airplane uninjured. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-10 He immediately turned the fuel selector valve off and made a forced landing to the runway. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-12 The airplane was consumed by fire. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-5 The airplane was destroyed. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-7 The flight originated from New Orleans, Louisiana, (NEW) about 25 minutes before the accident. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-2 Any errors in this report will be corrected when the final report has been completed. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-4 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed and no flight plan was filed. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-8 The private pilot stated that he departed NEW at about 1600, for the VFR local flight. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-6 The private pilot and one passenger reported no injuries. 
ntsb3849txt-1-5-5-0-3 On May 11, 2000, at about 1625 central daylight time, a Cessna 172H, N5107G, registered to a private owner, operating as a 14 CFR Part 91 personal flight, experienced an in-flight fire in the vicinity of Picayune, Mississippi. 
